</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="103" type="variation">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="103">Variation.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="103">
Males total length 3.6-5.0 (n = 2), females 5.0-7.3 (n = 6). Colour variations of this species mainly relate to the abdomen, where the 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Framenau &amp; Kuntner" authorityYear="2022" class="Arachnida" family="Araneidae" genus="Leviana" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Leviana folium" order="Araneae" pageId="0" pageNumber="103" rank="species" species="folium">Leviana folium</taxonomicName>
pattern can be more or less distinct (e.g. compare male and female in Figs 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 17" captionStartId="F17" captionText="Figure 17. Leviana mulieraria comb. nov., male (QM S 116640). A. Habitus, dorsal view; B. Habitus, ventral view; C. Left male pedipalp, ventral view; left male pedipalp, dorsal view. Scale bars: 2 mm (A, B); 0.2 mm (C, D)." httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/714534" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">17A</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 18" captionStartId="F18" captionText="Figure 18. Leviana mulieraria comb. nov., female (QM S 116639). A. Habitus, dorsal view; B. Habitus, ventral view; C. Epigyne, ventral view; D. Epigyne, posterior view. Scale bars: 2 mm (A, B); 0.2 mm (C, D)." httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/714535" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">18A</figureCitation>
). The scape was broken off in all six female specimens measured.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="103" type="remarks">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="103">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="103">
The holotype of 
<taxonomicName authority="Walckenaer, 1805" authorityName="Framenau &amp; Kuntner" authorityYear="2022" baseAuthorityName="Framenau &amp; Kuntner" baseAuthorityYear="2022" class="Arachnida" family="Araneidae" genus="Epeira" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Epeira mulieraria" order="Araneae" pageId="0" pageNumber="103" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mulieraria">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">Epeira mulieraria</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, described from a male of the Bradley collection, appears to be lost (see also 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.18195/issn.0312-3162.22(4).2005.265-292" author="Framenau, VW" journalOrPublisher="Records of the Western Australian Museum" pageId="0" pageNumber="103" pagination="265 - 292" refId="B9" refString="Framenau, VW, 2005. The wolf spider genus Artoria Thorell in Australia: new synonymies and generic transfers (Araneae, Lycosidae). Records of the Western Australian Museum 22: 265 - 292, DOI: https://doi.org/10.18195/issn.0312-3162.22(4).2005.265-292" title="The wolf spider genus Artoria Thorell in Australia: new synonymies and generic transfers (Araneae, Lycosidae)." url="https://doi.org/10.18195/issn.0312-3162.22(4).2005.265-292" volume="22" year="2005">Framenau 2005</bibRefCitation>
) as it could not be found in any of the historic museum collections in which 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Keyserling’s">Keyserling's</normalizedToken>
type material is deposited. However, the unique morphology of this species including its distinct abdominal colouration leave no doubt about the identity of this species and it is not considered necessary to designate a neotype here.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="103" type="life history and habitat preferences">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="103">Life history and habitat preferences.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="103">
Collecting numbers of 
<taxonomicName genus="L." lsidName="L. mulieraria" pageId="0" pageNumber="103" rank="species" species="mulieraria">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">L. mulieraria</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
comb. nov. are too low for an interpretation of its life cycles. Mature females were found from January to March, in May, August and October, mature males in March, May, August and October to November. Adults of this tropical species were therefore collected both in the wet and the dry seasons. Habitat descriptions include rainforest and vine thickets.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="103" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="103">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="103">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Framenau &amp; Kuntner" authorityYear="2022" baseAuthorityName="Keyserling" baseAuthorityYear="1887" class="Arachnida" family="Araneidae" genus="Leviana" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Leviana mulieraria" order="Araneae" pageId="0" pageNumber="103" rank="species" species="mulieraria">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">Leviana mulieraria</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
comb. nov. has been found in tropical northern Queensland, Northern Territory and Western Australia north of 16°S (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 14" captionStartId="F14" captionText="Figure 14. Distribution records of Leviana folium sp. nov., L. minima sp. nov. and L. mulieraria comb. nov." httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/714531" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">14</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
